    6. Model Deployment

    In [10]:
    def create_polynomial_model(degree, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val):
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)
    X_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_val_poly = poly.transform(X_val)

    model = LinearRegression()  # Use LinearRegression instead of Ridge
    model.fit(X_train_poly, y_train)

    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_poly)
    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val_poly)

    res = {
        "Degree": degree,
        "Train R2": r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred),
        "Validation R2": r2_score(y_val, y_val_pred),
        "Train MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred),
        "Validation MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_val_pred),
        "Train MAPE": mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train, y_train_pred),
        "Validation MAPE": mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_val, y_val_pred),
    }

    return model, poly, res
    In [11]:
    def train_multiple_models(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, degrees):
    models = {}
    results = []
    
    for deg in degrees:
        model, poly, res = create_polynomial_model(degree=deg, X_train=X_train, y_train=y_train, X_val=X_val, y_val=y_val)
        models[deg] = (model, poly)
        results.append(res)
    return models, pd.DataFrame(results)

bmi_train = train_data[['bmi']]
bmi_val = val_data[['bmi']]
bmi_test = test_data[['bmi']]

y_train = train_data['Y']
y_val = val_data['Y']
y_test = test_data['Y']

models, results_df = train_multiple_models(bmi_train, y_train, bmi_val, y_val, range(0,6))
results_df.set_index('Degree', inplace=True)

    def test_model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, degree):
    model, poly, _ = create_polynomial_model(degree, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)
    
    X_test_poly = poly.transform(X_test)
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test_poly)
    
    test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
    test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
    test_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
    
    results_df = pd.DataFrame({
        "Degree": [degree],
        "Test R2": [test_r2],
        "Test MAE": [test_mae],
        "Test MAPE": [test_mape]
    })

    return results_df

    10. Plotting the Graph of Train, Validation, and Test Data with the Fit of the Chosen Model

    In [14]:
    def plot_model(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, X_test, y_test, model, poly, degree):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

    plt.scatter(X_train, y_train, color='blue', label='Train Data', alpha=0.5)
    plt.scatter(X_val, y_val, color='orange', label='Validation Data', alpha=0.5)
    plt.scatter(X_test, y_test, color='green', label='Test Data', alpha=0.5)

    x_range = np.linspace(X_train.min(), X_train.max(), 100).reshape(-1, 1)
    x_range_poly = poly.transform(x_range)
    y_range_pred = model.predict(x_range_poly)

    plt.plot(x_range, y_range_pred, color='red', label=f'Best Fit Line', lw=2)

    plt.title(f'Train, Validation, and Test Data with Best Fit Line (Degree {degree})', fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel('BMI', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Disease Progression', fontsize=12)
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

    11. Writing the Equation of the Best Model (Degree 1)

    Since we selected a univariate polynomial regression model with degree 1, the equation of the best model will be a linear equation of the form:

    y = β0 + β1 ⋅ BMI

    Where:

    • β0 is the intercept
    • β1 is the coefficient of the BMI feature

    14. Conclusion:

    Best Model Selection:

    The univariate polynomial regression model of degree 1 performed the best based on the validation results, with the highest R-squared value and the lowest Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE).

    Model Performance:

    The R-squared on the test set indicates the proportion of variance explained by the model. The MAE and MAPE indicate that the model performs reasonably well in predicting diabetes progression based on BMI.

    Model Limitations:

  • The model only uses BMI as the predictor, which might not fully capture the complexity of diabetes progression. Other factors like age, blood pressure, and other medical data could improve predictions.

  • Polynomial regression, particularly with degree 1, assumes a linear relationship between BMI and diabetes progression, which might not fully reflect the real-world nonlinear relationship. For more complex patterns, higher-degree polynomial or other models may be needed.

  • The model is not robust to outliers and could potentially be affected by extreme values in BMI or disease progression.

    14. Conclusion¶

    Best Model Selection:

    The best model selected for predicting diabetes progression based on BMI is the Degree 3 Polynomial Regression model. This model was chosen based on the following considerations:

    • Higher Validation R² (0.412079): The Degree 3 model demonstrates better generalization on unseen data, as indicated by its higher Validation R² compared to the Degree 5 model.
    • Lower Validation MAE (49.676010): This model makes fewer errors when predicting on the validation set, which is important for ensuring accurate predictions.
    • Better Generalization Performance: Although the Degree 5 model performs slightly better on Train R², its Validation performance is worse. Since we want the model to generalize well to new data, Degree 3 is the better choice.

    Model Performance Summary¶

    • Train R²: 0.327586, indicating moderate fit on training data.
    • Validation R²: 0.412079, which shows better performance on unseen data compared to the Degree 5 model.
    • Test R²: 0.347896, showing the model generalizes reasonably well to the test set.
    • Test MAE: 52.418945, demonstrating acceptable error on test data.
    • Test MAPE: 0.52862, indicating the model's percentage errors are within an acceptable range.

    Model Limitations¶

    • Overfitting at Higher Degrees: Polynomial regression tends to overfit when the degree is too high, as it captures intricate details of the training data that do not generalize well.
    • Instability: Higher-degree polynomials can become unstable, leading to large variations in predictions for small changes in the input.
    • Non-linearity: While polynomial models capture non-linearity, they might not capture more complex patterns in the data, and higher degrees may introduce unnecessary complexity.

    Overall, the Degree 3 Polynomial Regression model strikes a good balance between generalization and simplicity. However, further improvements could be made by exploring other regression techniques, tuning the degree parameter more rigorously, or incorporating regularization methods to avoid overfitting.

    Training the Model¶

    In [39]:
    # to repeat Part 2 - we start training the model:
def train_decision_tree(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, depths):
    results = {}
    
    for depth in depths:
        dt = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=depth)
        dt.fit(X_train, y_train)

        train_pred = dt.predict(X_train)
        val_pred = dt.predict(X_val)

        train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, train_pred)
        val_r2 = r2_score(y_val, val_pred)
        train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, train_pred)
        val_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, val_pred)

        results[depth] = {
            "Train R2": train_r2,
            "Validation R2": val_r2,
            "Train MAE": train_mae,
            "Validation MAE": val_mae
        }

    return pd.DataFrame(results).T

Decision_Tree_Train_Results_df = train_decision_tree(bmi_train, y_train, bmi_val, y_val, depths)

        val_pred = dt.predict(X_val)

        train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, train_pred)
        val_r2 = r2_score(y_val, val_pred)
        test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, test_pred)

        train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, train_pred)
        val_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, val_pred)
        test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, test_pred)

        train_mape=mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train,train_pred)
        val_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_val, val_pred)
        test_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, test_pred)


        results[depth] = {
            "Test R2": test_r2,
            "Test MAE": test_mae,
            "Test MAPE":test_mape
        }

    Best Model Selection:

    The best model selected for predicting diabetes progression based on BMI is the Depth = 2 Decision Tree model. This model was chosen based on the following considerations:

    • Higher Validation R² (0.420408): The Depth = 2 model demonstrates better generalization on unseen data, as indicated by its higher Validation R² compared to the Depth = 3 model.
    • Lower Validation MAE (48.408951): This model makes fewer errors when predicting on the validation set, which is important for ensuring accurate predictions.

    Model Performance Summary¶

    • Train R²: 0.344644, indicating moderate fit on training data.
    • Validation R²: 0.420408, which shows better performance on unseen data compared to the Depth = 3 model.
    • Test R²: 0.341668, showing the model generalizes reasonably well to the test set.
    • Test MAE: 49.885704, demonstrating acceptable error on test data.
    • Test MAPE: 0.514326, indicating the model's percentage errors are within an acceptable range.

    Model Limitations¶

    • Overfitting at Larger Depths: Decision trees tend to overfit when the depth is too high, as they learn intricate details of the training data that do not generalize well.
    • Instability: Small changes in the data can lead to large variations in the tree structure, making decision trees sensitive to outliers or noise.
    • Bias towards Features with More Levels: Decision trees might favor features with more levels, which could lead to bias if certain features are less important for predicting the target variable.

    Overall, the Depth = 2 Decision Tree model provides a good balance between generalization and interpretability. However, further improvements in handling model complexity, tuning, and exploring ensemble methods could improve its performance and robustness.

    # for Part 2 -6 need to train kNN model
 
def train_knn(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, k_values):
    results = {}
    
    for k in k_values:
        knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=k)
        knn.fit(X_train, y_train)

        # Predict on train and validation sets
        train_pred = knn.predict(X_train)
        val_pred = knn.predict(X_val)

        train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, train_pred)
        val_r2 = r2_score(y_val, val_pred)
        train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, train_pred)
        val_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, val_pred)
        train_mape=mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train,train_pred)
        val_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_val, val_pred)
        

        results[k] = {
            "Train R2": train_r2,
            "Validation R2": val_r2,
            "Train MAE": train_mae,
            "Validation MAE": val_mae,
            "Train MAPE":train_mape,
            "Validation MAPE":val_mape
            
        }

    return pd.DataFrame(results).T

    14. Conclusion¶

    Best Model Selection:

    The best model chosen for predicting diabetes progression based on BMI is the k = 13 K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) model. This model was selected based on the following key points:

    • Higher Validation R² (0.436806): The model demonstrates a better ability to generalize to unseen data, which is crucial for making accurate predictions on future, unknown samples.
    • Lower Validation MAE (47.447552): The model's errors on the validation data are smaller, indicating more precise predictions compared to other models.
    • Lower Validation MAPE (0.327972): This suggests the model's percentage errors on validation data are relatively low, showing it performs more efficiently when estimating diabetes progression.

    Model Performance Summary¶

    • Train R²: 0.367506, which is slightly lower than the validation R², indicating some overfitting.
    • Test R²: 0.381277, showing good generalization on the test set.
    • Test MAE: 49.969001, a reasonable error margin for test predictions.
    • Test MAPE: 0.508882, which is acceptable but could be improved further.

    Model Limitations ¶

    • Scalability: As the dataset grows, the KNN algorithm can become slower due to its reliance on computing distances between all points during training and prediction. This could make it impractical for large datasets.
    • Sensitive to Noise: KNN is sensitive to noisy data and outliers. If the data contains irrelevant features or extreme values, it could negatively impact performance.
    • No Intrinsic Feature Selection: KNN does not have any built-in feature selection, so irrelevant or redundant features can degrade its performance. Feature engineering or dimensionality reduction methods like PCA could help in such cases.

    Overall, while the k = 13 KNN model provides a good balance of generalization and error reduction, there is room for improvement in its robustness and scalability, especially when dealing with large and noisy datasets.
